AUDIENCE: So, when you quit law,
did you have a fallback plan

00:46:42.970 --> 00:46:46.140
or a time limit as to, I'm going
to try this, if not go back

00:46:46.140 --> 00:46:46.640
to law?

00:46:46.640 --> 00:46:47.430
SCOTT JORDAN: No.

00:46:47.430 --> 00:46:49.050
No, I really didn't.

00:46:49.050 --> 00:46:50.590
I didn't think it through.

00:46:50.590 --> 00:46:54.560
I thought that the worst case
scenario was I go bankrupt.

00:46:54.560 --> 00:46:56.410
And in this country,
we're very fortunate.

00:46:56.410 --> 00:46:59.090
It's the best country in
the world to do business.

00:46:59.090 --> 00:47:00.340
You go bankrupt, who cares?

00:47:00.340 --> 00:47:01.390
You start over.

00:47:01.390 --> 00:47:03.180
I could always go back to law.

00:47:03.180 --> 00:47:06.030
That was my fallback plan,
and it was a miserable one.

00:47:06.030 --> 00:47:09.270
And every year, my law
license comes up for renewal.

00:47:09.270 --> 00:47:13.030
And I'm like, oh, do I
want to pay the $250?

00:47:13.030 --> 00:47:13.950
No, I'm ready.

00:47:13.950 --> 00:47:16.060
I really think I don't
need a fallback plan.

00:47:16.060 --> 00:47:20.550
And every year I still
send the damn check in.

00:47:20.550 --> 00:47:22.801
My life's a lawyer too,
and she wouldn't do it.

00:47:22.801 --> 00:47:23.300
Yeah.

00:47:23.300 --> 00:47:23.860
AUDIENCE: Hey Scott.

00:47:23.860 --> 00:47:24.590
Just a quick question.

00:47:24.590 --> 00:47:26.180
You mentioned Google
Analytics before.

00:47:26.180 --> 00:47:26.450
SCOTT JORDAN: Yeah.

00:47:26.450 --> 00:47:27.800
AUDIENCE: Can you
tell us a little bit

00:47:27.800 --> 00:47:30.050
about how you use that or
if that's been instrumental

00:47:30.050 --> 00:47:31.502
in any of your success?

00:47:31.502 --> 00:47:33.210
SCOTT JORDAN: It's a
love-hate situation.

00:47:33.210 --> 00:47:34.200
There's so much--

00:47:34.200 --> 00:47:34.910
AUDIENCE: What do you
love and what do you hate?

00:47:34.910 --> 00:47:36.800
SCOTT JORDAN: I love
the amount of data

00:47:36.800 --> 00:47:38.240
and I hate the amount of data.

00:47:41.910 --> 00:47:45.120
I was a very early adopter.

00:47:45.120 --> 00:47:47.930
We've been on Google Analytics
since the beginning of time.

00:47:47.930 --> 00:47:50.910
And I love the fact
that within a second

00:47:50.910 --> 00:47:53.720
I can see how things
are performing.

00:47:53.720 --> 00:47:57.680
And as a result, it puts
a lot of pressure on me

00:47:57.680 --> 00:47:59.570
because I know that
if I do something--

00:47:59.570 --> 00:48:03.700
like I'm on this trip, and
my car has QR codes on it.

00:48:03.700 --> 00:48:06.930
And who uses QR codes,
especially with a car

00:48:06.930 --> 00:48:09.780
driving 70 miles an hour?

00:48:09.780 --> 00:48:12.090
But I look at the Google
Analytics every day,

00:48:12.090 --> 00:48:16.590
and it makes you a
slave to information.

00:48:16.590 --> 00:48:20.930
I really wish that there were
better human beings involved

00:48:20.930 --> 00:48:23.430
in my organization who can
condense the information

00:48:23.430 --> 00:48:24.680
to give me actionable items.

00:48:24.680 --> 00:48:27.240
I used to look at it
religiously daily, twice a day.

00:48:27.240 --> 00:48:27.885
It was up.

00:48:27.885 --> 00:48:30.720
I haven't looked at it in years.

00:48:30.720 --> 00:48:33.380
I rely on my wife to tell me
if we're doing well or not.

00:48:33.380 --> 00:48:35.713
And at the end of every day,
I say, how did we do today?

00:48:35.713 --> 00:48:37.350
It was a good day,
bad day, no numbers.

00:48:37.350 --> 00:48:40.590
We have never done a strategic
plan, never done any.

00:48:40.590 --> 00:48:45.782
I don't review, just
keep trying to focus

00:48:45.782 --> 00:48:47.240
on what I think is
the right thing,

00:48:47.240 --> 00:48:49.260
and it's proved
pretty good for me.

00:48:51.840 --> 00:48:54.510
AUDIENCE: Your background
is being a lawyer,

00:48:54.510 --> 00:48:56.320
and you're not happy about it.

00:48:56.320 --> 00:49:00.260
But it enabled you to
come up with the fund

00:49:00.260 --> 00:49:04.070
to start this business now.

00:49:04.070 --> 00:49:07.160
I came from Japan three years
ago because of the disaster,

00:49:07.160 --> 00:49:10.590
and I pretty much had
to start from scratch

00:49:10.590 --> 00:49:12.680
my life in the United States.

00:49:12.680 --> 00:49:14.160
And I had a big dream.

00:49:14.160 --> 00:49:18.590
And I am actually starting a
business, but the challenge

00:49:18.590 --> 00:49:20.700
with raising the money.

00:49:20.700 --> 00:49:24.910
And I got people who
invest, but the people

00:49:24.910 --> 00:49:26.970
has a lot of fear
of losing the money.

00:49:26.970 --> 00:49:30.470
And so I'm dealing with that.

00:49:30.470 --> 00:49:36.220
And so I guess the question
is, if you weren't coming

00:49:36.220 --> 00:49:38.700
from the background
of having money,

00:49:38.700 --> 00:49:40.590
what would you have
done, and would you

00:49:40.590 --> 00:49:46.160
choose people whose hard-earned
money and have a lot of fear

00:49:46.160 --> 00:49:47.280
around it?

00:49:47.280 --> 00:49:49.427
Is that a good investors?

00:49:49.427 --> 00:49:50.760
What would you say in that case?

00:49:50.760 --> 00:49:52.176
SCOTT JORDAN: So,
when I started--

00:49:52.176 --> 00:49:54.260
this is a great
question-- I always

00:49:54.260 --> 00:49:56.890
thought you started a business
with other people's money.

00:49:56.890 --> 00:49:59.070
I just thought
that's what you did.

00:49:59.070 --> 00:50:03.220
And I actually started
with a home equity loan.

00:50:03.220 --> 00:50:06.040
It was $60,000 was
the seed money.

00:50:06.040 --> 00:50:10.300
And at the time-- this was
before the real estate crash--

00:50:10.300 --> 00:50:12.450
it was fairly easy to get
a home equity loan just

00:50:12.450 --> 00:50:16.640
based on credit score, and that
wasn't a great deal of money

00:50:16.640 --> 00:50:17.700
to start a business.

00:50:17.700 --> 00:50:19.930
That is all the
capital I used to start

00:50:19.930 --> 00:50:22.090
my business, effectively.

00:50:22.090 --> 00:50:26.360
But to me, that was a lot
of money, to invest $60,000.

00:50:26.360 --> 00:50:29.200
But I was prepared to
lose it, and if I lost it,

00:50:29.200 --> 00:50:33.930
I guess I would have lost my
house, which would have sucked.

00:50:33.930 --> 00:50:36.220
But I looked at all sorts
of different alternatives.

00:50:36.220 --> 00:50:37.860
I looked to SBA loans.

00:50:37.860 --> 00:50:39.420
I looked at having investors.

00:50:39.420 --> 00:50:42.380
And in fact one guy who
sits on my advisory board

00:50:42.380 --> 00:50:46.030
along with Steve Wozniak, who
is on my board of advisors,

00:50:46.030 --> 00:50:49.840
which I'm proud to say.

00:50:49.840 --> 00:50:54.200
One guy came in, and I said,
this is right after 9/11.

00:50:54.200 --> 00:50:55.610
My business was doing horribly.

00:50:55.610 --> 00:50:56.550
Everyone's was.

00:50:56.550 --> 00:50:57.890
It's a luxury item.

00:50:57.890 --> 00:51:01.970
You don't need a
SCOTTeVEST to travel,

00:51:01.970 --> 00:51:04.570
which I'll tell a
related story to.

00:51:04.570 --> 00:51:07.050
And he looked at my
books, and he said,

00:51:07.050 --> 00:51:08.990
I don't think you
need investors.

00:51:08.990 --> 00:51:11.910
I think you can do it, because
before 9/11 I was already

00:51:11.910 --> 00:51:13.910
starting to be
cash flow positive.

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:17.430
And then after 9/11 with
the holidays coming up--

00:51:17.430 --> 00:51:18.990
he convinced me.

00:51:18.990 --> 00:51:22.200
And he stood to gain because
if he could have raised money

00:51:22.200 --> 00:51:24.340
for me, he would
have gotten a piece,

00:51:24.340 --> 00:51:26.299
and it would have been
profitable for him.

00:51:26.299 --> 00:51:27.340
And he said, don't do it.

00:51:27.340 --> 00:51:29.160
And it was the smartest
thing I ever did.

00:51:29.160 --> 00:51:31.340
Because the time
and energy you will

00:51:31.340 --> 00:51:35.450
spend keeping your investors up
to date and keeping them happy

00:51:35.450 --> 00:51:37.430
and wondering when
their exit strategy is

00:51:37.430 --> 00:51:39.840
and wondering why you
made this decision,

00:51:39.840 --> 00:51:42.450
I'd much rather dedicate
that to the business.

00:51:42.450 --> 00:51:46.840
So in my case, it
wasn't the money

00:51:46.840 --> 00:51:50.740
that I made while practicing
law, because most of that

00:51:50.740 --> 00:51:52.970
was spent on living
big in Chicago.

00:51:52.970 --> 00:51:56.680
You don't save that
much money at that age,

00:51:56.680 --> 00:51:57.840
as much as you should.

00:51:57.840 --> 00:52:02.320
But having the luxury of a
wife working full time that

00:52:02.320 --> 00:52:06.380
was completely supportive of
the idea, which was awesome.

00:52:06.380 --> 00:52:07.880
I couldn't have
done it without her.

00:52:07.880 --> 00:52:10.950
And to this day, all of my
success is because of her.

00:52:10.950 --> 00:52:14.740
She is the hardest working
woman-- person-- in the world.

00:52:14.740 --> 00:52:17.680
She gets to the office
every day at 12:30,

00:52:17.680 --> 00:52:19.930
and she leaves the
next day at 4:00.

00:52:19.930 --> 00:52:24.990
She puts in 16-hour days, and
she's there processing orders.

00:52:24.990 --> 00:52:26.090
She's like a machine.

00:52:26.090 --> 00:52:28.200
She just loves the
work, and she makes sure

00:52:28.200 --> 00:52:30.410
that we don't make
mistakes and we

00:52:30.410 --> 00:52:32.590
don't make bad hiring decisions.

00:52:32.590 --> 00:52:36.114
It's hard, because you have to
have a home to borrow against.

00:52:36.114 --> 00:52:37.530
But, you know,
what I would advise

00:52:37.530 --> 00:52:39.220
you is find a
business that doesn't

00:52:39.220 --> 00:52:41.340
require a lot of capital.

00:52:41.340 --> 00:52:44.930
Service businesses,
websites, do something

00:52:44.930 --> 00:52:48.320
that doesn't require
the capital investment.

00:52:48.320 --> 00:52:52.092
Most businesses in America
are service businesses.

00:52:52.092 --> 00:52:54.860
AUDIENCE: But what
about the passion?

00:52:54.860 --> 00:52:56.820
I have this background
of writing a first book

00:52:56.820 --> 00:53:00.740
on raw food diet for Japan, and
I became the raw food person

00:53:00.740 --> 00:53:01.510
in Japan.

00:53:01.510 --> 00:53:04.620
And since this
last three years, I

00:53:04.620 --> 00:53:08.490
have just followed my other
passion, which is language.

00:53:08.490 --> 00:53:12.640
But I really want to start this
juice bar, and I got the place,

00:53:12.640 --> 00:53:15.590
and dealing with
this PG&amp;E building,

00:53:15.590 --> 00:53:16.880
which is huge company.

00:53:16.880 --> 00:53:20.360
And they're just dragging
us along for six months now.

00:53:20.360 --> 00:53:24.070
And I'm at the point I
don't know what to do now.

00:53:24.070 --> 00:53:27.050
What can I do to make
this move faster?

00:53:27.050 --> 00:53:27.784
What should I--

00:53:27.784 --> 00:53:29.200
SCOTT JORDAN: Well,
if some things

00:53:29.200 --> 00:53:31.430
are outside your control,
you can't blame yourself

00:53:31.430 --> 00:53:33.132
for doing that path.

00:53:33.132 --> 00:53:34.590
I'd find if there
are other places.

00:53:34.590 --> 00:53:37.010
If you're really
passionate about that idea,

00:53:37.010 --> 00:53:38.970
find a way to pursue it.

00:53:38.970 --> 00:53:40.570
And if you need
investors to do it,

00:53:40.570 --> 00:53:42.990
then find some
friends and family,

00:53:42.990 --> 00:53:45.740
because they really
understand you.

00:53:45.740 --> 00:53:48.780
But go into it
really passionate.

00:53:48.780 --> 00:53:51.180
If you are going to
fail, there is no-- there

00:53:51.180 --> 00:53:53.070
was no plan B for me.

00:53:53.070 --> 00:53:54.050
There was none.

00:53:54.050 --> 00:53:59.110
And I really, I painted myself
intentionally into a corner,

00:53:59.110 --> 00:54:01.550
because I knew I had to succeed.

00:54:01.550 --> 00:54:04.555
Because failure was not
a good option for me.

00:54:04.555 --> 00:54:05.680
AUDIENCE: Thank you, Scott.

00:54:05.680 --> 00:54:06.471
SCOTT JORDAN: Sure.

00:54:06.471 --> 00:54:08.610
AUDIENCE: I just glanced
through the Amazon review

00:54:08.610 --> 00:54:09.410
you mentioned.

00:54:09.410 --> 00:54:12.992
I noticed there are entries
like a kind of wish list

00:54:12.992 --> 00:54:14.450
of which you
mentioned in the book,

00:54:14.450 --> 00:54:16.730
like a detail like
how you started

00:54:16.730 --> 00:54:21.590
with finding manufacturing,
handling shipping, growing

00:54:21.590 --> 00:54:23.090
customer business.

00:54:23.090 --> 00:54:27.360
I want to take this opportunity
to satisfy those curious souls.

00:54:27.360 --> 00:54:30.430
And it's kind of related to
that gentleman's question,

00:54:30.430 --> 00:54:32.570
like how you're growing.

00:54:32.570 --> 00:54:35.700
But instead of making it that
loaded question, maybe just

00:54:35.700 --> 00:54:38.160
like when you get
that idea, you get

00:54:38.160 --> 00:54:42.910
that home equity fund, how do
you start getting manufacturing

00:54:42.910 --> 00:54:45.243
and actually start the business?

00:54:45.243 --> 00:54:47.820
SCOTT JORDAN: I am
the only apparel

00:54:47.820 --> 00:54:51.970
maker and maybe the only
manufacturer in the country

00:54:51.970 --> 00:54:55.820
and maybe the world who has
been manufacturing in Asia

00:54:55.820 --> 00:55:00.840
and has never been to
my factories, ever.

00:55:00.840 --> 00:55:02.590
I don't know if I
should be proud of that,

00:55:02.590 --> 00:55:06.380
but I'm still working with the
same factories I started with.

00:55:06.380 --> 00:55:09.610
I have great
inspection companies.

00:55:09.610 --> 00:55:10.660
I use Skype.

00:55:10.660 --> 00:55:11.380
I use video.

00:55:11.380 --> 00:55:12.880
I have great correspondence.

00:55:12.880 --> 00:55:15.700
So I'm going to start there.

00:55:15.700 --> 00:55:17.840
If you ask someone,
in my case once I

00:55:17.840 --> 00:55:21.260
start telling people I wanted
to make something in China,

00:55:21.260 --> 00:55:22.950
everyone knew someone
who knew someone

00:55:22.950 --> 00:55:24.825
who knew someone who
made something in China,

00:55:24.825 --> 00:55:27.860
and they could get you
there one way or another.

00:55:27.860 --> 00:55:31.360
The problem was that everyone
along the way wants a cut.

00:55:31.360 --> 00:55:32.590
Everyone's hand is out.

00:55:32.590 --> 00:55:36.110
I mean, it's like old
school merchant business.

00:55:36.110 --> 00:55:37.160
It really is.

00:55:37.160 --> 00:55:41.360
So fortunately, one of
my factories, the one I'm

00:55:41.360 --> 00:55:45.120
still working, one of my
major ones, 14 years straight.

00:55:45.120 --> 00:55:48.890
And my factories have all
come out to Ketchum, Idaho.

00:55:48.890 --> 00:55:51.200
It's like a two-day
trip to come out

00:55:51.200 --> 00:55:53.680
to visit us instead of
me going out to them.

00:55:53.680 --> 00:55:55.110
I'd like to change
that, because I

00:55:55.110 --> 00:55:58.510
think I do need-- they're
an extension of my company.

00:55:58.510 --> 00:56:02.550
So the answer is
just passionately

00:56:02.550 --> 00:56:05.430
decide what the end game
is and work backwards.

00:56:05.430 --> 00:56:08.470
You need a factory in China.

00:56:08.470 --> 00:56:11.360
You need a place
for your juice bar.

00:56:11.360 --> 00:56:13.160
What are the steps
it's going to take?

00:56:13.160 --> 00:56:15.530
Where's the critical path?

00:56:15.530 --> 00:56:17.070
I do everything that way.

00:56:17.070 --> 00:56:20.950
And anything that is a
third party I do first,

00:56:20.950 --> 00:56:24.970
because I know anything
that's out of mind control,

00:56:24.970 --> 00:56:27.550
I want to start earlier.

00:56:27.550 --> 00:56:30.110
It's critical path.

00:56:30.110 --> 00:56:32.390
AUDIENCE: One of your
tenets was, a day of action

00:56:32.390 --> 00:56:34.405
is better than a
week of thinking.

00:56:34.405 --> 00:56:38.360
A lot of people I know, even in
Google, they have great ideas,

00:56:38.360 --> 00:56:39.994
and they try to work
on them part time.

00:56:39.994 --> 00:56:41.910
Obviously it sounds like
you went cold turkey,

00:56:41.910 --> 00:56:43.740
the cold turkey route, where
you just said, hey, look.

00:56:43.740 --> 00:56:44.605
I'm going to go full time.

00:56:44.605 --> 00:56:46.160
I'm going to quit
my job, do X, Y, Z.

00:56:46.160 --> 00:56:49.990
How do you think about
what you gain psychically

00:56:49.990 --> 00:56:53.110
by making that full plunge
versus the advantages of having

00:56:53.110 --> 00:56:56.610
a job and working
in your free time?

00:56:56.610 --> 00:56:58.300
SCOTT JORDAN: I
think it's dramatic.

00:56:58.300 --> 00:57:01.320
I mean, to say, I'm
jumping in full time.

00:57:01.320 --> 00:57:06.140
I'm painting myself in a
corner-- the flip side of that

00:57:06.140 --> 00:57:09.530
is people who go into a
business with an exit strategy.

00:57:09.530 --> 00:57:11.090
I don't have an exit strategy.

00:57:11.090 --> 00:57:15.200
I want to go in thinking what
today, tomorrow, next year

00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:15.720
looks like.

00:57:15.720 --> 00:57:18.970
But I don't want to worry about
when I'm going to sell out.

00:57:18.970 --> 00:57:21.950
So I think it's really
important that if you are going

00:57:21.950 --> 00:57:24.280
to make-- now, it doesn't
mean that you just come up

00:57:24.280 --> 00:57:26.510
with an idea, and
you love the idea,

00:57:26.510 --> 00:57:29.590
and before you do your research
you quit your great-paying job

00:57:29.590 --> 00:57:31.840
at Google or wherever
you are, and you just

00:57:31.840 --> 00:57:33.280
go off and running.

00:57:33.280 --> 00:57:36.470
But you need to
know when to jump.

00:57:36.470 --> 00:57:38.930
You need to know when
to take that first step.

00:57:38.930 --> 00:57:39.910
And then you know what?

00:57:39.910 --> 00:57:43.090
After you take that first
step, take another one.

00:57:43.090 --> 00:57:44.450
Don't pause.

00:57:44.450 --> 00:57:46.090
Keep going.

00:57:46.090 --> 00:57:50.010
And that's what I did, because
I got affirmation along the way.

00:57:50.010 --> 00:57:52.510
But not everyone--
when I told people--

00:57:52.510 --> 00:57:55.280
I was making really
good money as a lawyer.

00:57:55.280 --> 00:57:57.360
I told people, I'm
going to stop and form

00:57:57.360 --> 00:57:59.930
this company called
SCOTTeVEST about pockets,

00:57:59.930 --> 00:58:01.315
they thought I was crazy.

00:58:04.090 --> 00:58:05.320
People fell in two camps.

00:58:05.320 --> 00:58:07.930
They thought I was
brilliant or crazy.

00:58:07.930 --> 00:58:09.220
There was no one in between.

00:58:09.220 --> 00:58:12.740
No one was like, ah, well,
that might be a good idea.

00:58:12.740 --> 00:58:15.010
And that's kind of been
the story of my life.

00:58:15.010 --> 00:58:18.990
I kind of tend to be a little
controversial, I guess.

00:58:18.990 --> 00:58:21.070
So I want to thank you guys.

00:58:21.070 --> 00:58:22.885
This has been fun
for my first speech.

